@Jane Wheelaghan

A sedan is, I believe, AmE usage for what would be a "saloon" in BrE---so a "three-box" car with a boot as a separate, lidded compartment, in contrast to a hatchback.

It's interesting (at least to me) how "saloon" followed different trajectories in AmE and BrE. Both started off using the word to designate public spaces, but BrE seems to have been influenced specifically by the "saloon car" on trains, which had an association with enclosed, comfortable travel. So when cars were first built with relatively spacious, enclosed passenger compartments, and room for luggage, they became "saloon cars".

